ey, Fiona Rae, Lynda Benglis, Karen Carson, and many others. Hickey discusses their work as work, bringing politics and gender into the discussion only where it seems warranted by the art itself. The resulting book is not only a deep engagement with some of the most influential and innovative contemporary artists, but also a reflection on the life and role of the critic: the decisions, judgments, politics, and ethics that critics negotiate throughout their careers in the art world. Always engaging, often controversial, and never dull, Dave Hickey is a writer who gets people excited—and talking—about art. 25 Women will thrill his many fans, and make him plenty of new ones.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aArt criticism. 0aWomen artists. 7aART / General.2bisacsh  aart history, criticism, fine arts, female artists, photography, american literature, essays, essay collection, anthology, engaging, witty, illuminating, powerful women, compilation, joan mitchell, bridget riley, fiona rae, lynda benglis, karen carson, politics, gender, womens issues, ethics, controversial topics, social problems, elizabeth murray, influential people, sculpture, sculptors, performance, music.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226249148423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226249148/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles